In contrast to the requirements for formula_30 to have a limit at a point formula_158, which do not constrain the behavior of formula_30 at formula_158 itself, the following two conditions, in addition to the existence of formula_161, must also hold in order for formula_30 to be continuous at formula_158: (i) formula_30 must be defined at formula_158, i.e., formula_158 is in the domain of formula_30; "and" (ii) formula_168 as formula_169. The definition above actually applies to any domain formula_131 that does not contain an isolated point, or equivalently, formula_131 where every formula_152 is a limit point of formula_131. A more general definition applying to formula_174 with a general domain formula_175 is the following:

