Definition. If formula_136 is a subset of the real numbers, we say a function formula_174 is uniformly continuous on formula_136 if, for any formula_40, there exists a formula_41 such that for all formula_214, formula_215 implies that formula_216"."

Explicitly, when a function is uniformly continuous on formula_136, the choice of formula_49 needed to fulfill the definition must work for "all of" formula_136 for a given formula_50. In contrast, when a function is continuous at every point formula_179 (or said to be continuous on formula_136), the choice of formula_49 may depend on both formula_50 "and" formula_158. Importantly, in contrast to simple continuity, uniform continuity is a property of a function that only makes sense with a specified domain; to speak of uniform continuity at a single point formula_158 is meaningless.

On a compact set, it is easily shown that all continuous functions are uniformly continuous. If formula_131 is a bounded noncompact subset of formula_1, then there exists formula_105 that is continuous but not uniformly continuous. As a simple example, consider formula_230 defined by formula_231. By choosing points close to 0, we can always make formula_232 for any single choice of formula_41, for a given formula_40.

Definition. Let formula_235 be an interval on the real line. A function formula_236 is said to be absolutely continuous on formula_143 if for every positive number formula_50, there is a positive number formula_49 such that whenever a finite sequence of pairwise disjoint sub-intervals formula_240 of formula_143 satisfies
